s philosophy of repetition; Emmanuel Levinas's concept of "proximity," and in further circuit: the philosophies of Bergson, Kant, Leibniz, Heidegger himself, and more. Exploring the interpretative and generative potential of the mise en abyme for continental thought, Dickmann reveals new points of resonance between various philosophical topics including, aesthetics, ethics, time, logic, mirroring, play, and signification.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aMise en abyme (Narration) 0aMise en abyme (Narration). 0aPoststructuralism. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Critical Theory. 4aPhilosophy : German Idealism. 4aPhilosophy : Post Structuralism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Structuralism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438474014423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438474014/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles